Description.LocalizedString: The withered seed of a pustula flower, slowly turning to dust.
A sprout paradoxically enlivened by its death.
A tight pustula bulb showing signs of the unusual orange liquid within.
A vibrant flower, weeping with a mysterious substance, signaling the season of a new blight.
The document that brought Adam to Japan and, in turn, The Entity’s realm.
The primary weapon in Nea’s arsenal against the establishment.
Adam’s unreliable scooter with an ironic name. Though he had other names for it, they’re better left unsaid.
Nea had a message to send and she wrote it in paint.
Nea’s iconic tag that can still be seen along city streets.
The thin strap that’s hopefully enough to control a sheriff’s dog.
A prize-winning pig whose victory was celebrated with a good ol’ fashioned barbeque.
An item cherished by The Observer for its quaint simplicity.
A flyer that rallied against the pollution of a local water supply.
A fun alternative to corndogs that the kids are sure to love.
Aged whiskey that helped The Observer through the eternal nights.
A crow that underwent the careful examination of The Observer, in an attempt to decipher the realm’s secrets.
A book that helped Adam stumble his way through conversations in Japan.
A picturesque setting that glosses over the child imprisoned within.
A keychain that captures the likeness of The Clown’s deformed horse.
A carnival prize with a gaping entry wound that bleeds stuffing.
A sample of nerve tissue that reacts strangely to The Fog. A means to escape or a dead end?
The mayor’s prized car, having recently undergone a custom paint job.
He may not have been born mad, but the confines of his home left him that way.
He expressed himself in violence, and from him death arose.
He wouldn’t allow himself to be confined again. He’d fight back.
They couldn’t catch him. And if they did... he’d kill them.
He fought for his freedom with blood. The nightmare was over, while for others it was just beginning.
Nea was prepared to fight any injustice. There was no compromise.
When her friends rose up, she took to the streets with them.
She refused to follow the rules.
Her spray paint was her weapon in the fight, her skateboard a means of escape.
The outcome was worse than she expected—she had to flee fast.
A jack-o-lantern that became a test subject for blight serum.
A bucket of candy perks. No one seems to have touched the This Is Not Happening candies.
The crows don’t seem afraid of this at all...
A good mask makes the murderer.
